Ultimately, it would be pretty cool if we could do something like:
- create a new EC2 instance and load the JMH runner JAR with the benchmarks
- read a baseline file from S3
- run the tests
- write the results to Tranquility Server for ingestion into Druid
- terminate the EC2 instance

### Metrics and Threshold

JMH's benchmark "score" is calculated as the mean result over all the runs (not including warmups). It is supplemented with a "score error", which is the mean error at a 99.9% confidence interval. If the confidence interval is too wide (due to not enough iterations or wild variance during the iterations), the score error will be large proportional to the score. I think it makes sense to fail test runs if the scoreError/score ratio exceeds a certain threshold, since this means that the result is unreliable and not that meaningful anyway. This could be because of too few iterations, too much variance going on in the testing environment, or a badly written test. In any case, comparing say a baseline of [1000ops/sec] with a result of [1000ops/sec +/- 1000ops/sec] is a pretty useless comparison and should be a failure.

We can also get percentiles from the JMH results (in the above example I'm storing the p50, p90, p95, and p99). I'm undecided as to whether it is really necessary to capture percentiles as I believe performance benchmark results should be fairly normally distributed and hence the mean + CI should be good. Looking for any thoughts on this.

### Alternatives

The primary alternative I see to building our own runner is to use JMH's Maven script to build a benchmarks.jar file, configure it to write the results to a file, and then write scripts to parse and act on the output generated by calling `java -jar target/benchmarks.jar`. I think building our own runner has a number of advantages over this, the main ones being the ability to check before running the benchmarks to make sure we have baselines available, and the ability to output the results to a format we want directly from their Java RunResult object instead of parsing their output file.

There are also plugins for [Jenkins](https://github.com/brianfromoregon/jmh-plugin) and [TeamCity](https://github.com/presidentio/teamcity-plugin-jmh) available; I haven't looked too much into them as I don't know that we want to tie ourselves to any specific build framework (and I like the idea of being able to emit results in a format that we can ingest into Druid).

Thoughts?
